<h1>Complete Spanish Pronunciation and IPA Guide</h1>

<p>
This guide focuses on <strong>standard European/Castilian Spanish</strong>, similar to educated speech from Madrid or north-central Spain.
Since you live in <strong>Málaga</strong>, Andalusian pronunciation notes are included so you can understand what locals do differently.
</p>

<div class="note">
<p><strong>IPA notation:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li><code>/ /</code> = phoneme, the mental sound category.</li>
  <li><code>[ ]</code> = exact pronunciation or allophone.</li>
</ul>
<p>
Example: Spanish <code>/b/</code> can be pronounced as a full stop <code>[b]</code> or a softer approximant <code>[β̞]</code>, depending on position.
</p>
</div>

<h2>1. Big Differences Between Spanish and English Pronunciation</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Spanish vowels are pure.</strong> There is no English-style schwa reduction in normal careful speech.</li>
  <li><strong>Spanish rhythm is more syllable-timed.</strong> Every syllable tends to be clearer than in English.</li>
  <li><strong>Spanish <code>/p t k/</code> are not aspirated.</strong> English <em>pie, tie, kite</em> have a puff of air; Spanish <em>pa, ta, ca</em> do not.</li>
  <li><strong>Spanish <code>/t/</code> and <code>/d/</code> are dental.</strong> The tongue touches the back of the upper teeth, not the English alveolar ridge.</li>
  <li><strong>B and V are the same sound</strong> in modern Spanish.</li>
  <li><strong>Standard Castilian distinguishes <code>/s/</code> and <code>/θ/</code>.</strong> This is the difference between <em>casa</em> and <em>caza</em>.</li>
  <li><strong>Written H is silent.</strong> <em>hola</em> = <code>/ˈola/</code>.</li>
</ul>

<h2>2. Spanish Vowels</h2>

<p>
Spanish has five basic vowel phonemes. They are short, clear, stable, and do not usually reduce.
</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>IPA</th>
<th>Example</th>
<th>Articulation</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><code>/a/</code></td>
<td><strong>a</strong>gua <code>/ˈaɣwa/</code>, c<strong>a</strong>sa <code>/ˈkasa/</code></td>
<td>Open central/front vowel. Jaw open, lips neutral. Similar to a clean “ah,” but not too far back.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/e/</code></td>
<td>m<strong>e</strong>sa <code>/ˈmesa/</code>, p<strong>e</strong>ro <code>/ˈpeɾo/</code></td>
<td>Mid front unrounded vowel. Tongue forward, jaw moderately open. Do not make it into English <code>/eɪ/</code>.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/i/</code></td>
<td>s<strong>í</strong> <code>/si/</code>, v<strong>i</strong>no <code>/ˈbino/</code></td>
<td>High front unrounded vowel. Similar to English “ee,” but shorter and cleaner.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/o/</code></td>
<td>s<strong>o</strong>lo <code>/ˈsolo/</code>, n<strong>o</strong> <code>/no/</code></td>
<td>Mid back rounded vowel. Do not pronounce it like English <code>/oʊ/</code>; avoid the glide.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/u/</code></td>
<td>t<strong>ú</strong> <code>/tu/</code>, l<strong>u</strong>na <code>/ˈluna/</code></td>
<td>High back rounded vowel. Lips rounded, tongue high and back. Shorter and purer than English “oo.”</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h3>Important Vowel Rule</h3>

<p>
English often turns unstressed vowels into schwa <code>/ə/</code>. Spanish does not do this in standard pronunciation.
</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Word</th>
<th>Spanish Pronunciation</th>
<th>Do Not Say</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>banana</td>
<td><code>/baˈnana/</code></td>
<td>Not “buh-NA-nuh”</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>teléfono</td>
<td><code>/teˈlefono/</code></td>
<td>Not “tuh-LEH-fuh-no”</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Madrid</td>
<td><code>/maˈðɾið/</code> or careful <code>/maˈdɾid/</code></td>
<td>Not “muh-DRID”</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h3>Diphthongs and Glides</h3>

<p>
Spanish also has glides, usually written with <code>i/y</code> or <code>u</code>. In IPA these are often written <code>[j]</code> and <code>[w]</code>.
</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>IPA</th>
<th>Example</th>
<th>Description</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><code>/ja/</code>, <code>/je/</code>, <code>/jo/</code></td>
<td>t<strong>ie</strong>ne <code>/ˈtjene/</code>, famil<strong>ia</strong> <code>/faˈmilja/</code></td>
<td>Quick <code>/i/</code>-like movement before a vowel.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/wa/</code>, <code>/we/</code>, <code>/wo/</code></td>
<td>c<strong>ua</strong>tro <code>/ˈkwatɾo/</code>, b<strong>ue</strong>no <code>/ˈbweno/</code></td>
<td>Quick <code>/u/</code>-like movement before a vowel.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/ai̯/</code>, <code>/ei̯/</code>, <code>/oi̯/</code></td>
<td><strong>ai</strong>re <code>/ˈai̯ɾe/</code>, l<strong>ey</strong> <code>/lei̯/</code>, h<strong>oy</strong> <code>/oi̯/</code></td>
<td>Falling diphthongs ending in an <code>i</code>-like glide.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/au̯/</code>, <code>/eu̯/</code></td>
<td>c<strong>au</strong>sa <code>/ˈkau̯sa/</code>, <strong>Eu</strong>ropa <code>/eu̯ˈɾopa/</code></td>
<td>Falling diphthongs ending in a <code>u</code>-like glide.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h2>3. Spanish Consonants in IPA</h2>

<h3>Stops and Stop-like Consonants</h3>

<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>IPA</th>
<th>Example</th>
<th>Articulation</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><code>/p/</code></td>
<td><strong>p</strong>an <code>/pan/</code></td>
<td>Voiceless bilabial stop. Close both lips, release without strong aspiration. Spanish <code>/p/</code> is softer than English initial <em>p</em>.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/b/</code></td>
<td><strong>b</strong>eso <code>/ˈbeso/</code>, <strong>v</strong>ino <code>/ˈbino/</code></td>
<td>B and V are the same phoneme in Spanish. Pronounced <code>[b]</code> after a pause or nasal; usually softer <code>[β̞]</code> between vowels.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/t/</code></td>
<td><strong>t</strong>aza <code>/ˈtaθa/</code></td>
<td>Voiceless dental stop <code>[t̪]</code>. Tongue touches the back of the upper teeth. No English-style aspiration.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/d/</code></td>
<td><strong>d</strong>ía <code>/ˈdia/</code></td>
<td>Voiced dental stop or approximant. Strong <code>[d̪]</code> after pause, nasal, or <code>/l/</code>; softer <code>[ð̞]</code> between vowels.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/k/</code></td>
<td><strong>c</strong>asa <code>/ˈkasa/</code>, <strong>qu</strong>eso <code>/ˈkeso/</code></td>
<td>Voiceless velar stop. Back of tongue touches soft palate. No strong puff of air.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/ɡ/</code></td>
<td><strong>g</strong>ato <code>/ˈɡato/</code>, <strong>gu</strong>ía <code>/ˈɡia/</code></td>
<td>Voiced velar stop or approximant. Strong <code>[ɡ]</code> after pause or nasal; softer <code>[ɣ̞]</code> between vowels.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h3>Fricatives and Similar Sounds</h3>

<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>IPA</th>
<th>Example</th>
<th>Articulation</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><code>/f/</code></td>
<td><strong>f</strong>amilia <code>/faˈmilja/</code></td>
<td>Voiceless labiodental fricative. Upper teeth touch lower lip; blow air.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/θ/</code></td>
<td><strong>z</strong>apato <code>/θaˈpato/</code>, <strong>c</strong>inco <code>/ˈθinko/</code></td>
<td>Voiceless dental fricative, like English <em>th</em> in <em>think</em>. This is used in standard Castilian Spanish for <strong>z</strong> and <strong>c</strong> before <strong>e/i</strong>.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/s/</code></td>
<td><strong>s</strong>ol <code>/sol/</code>, ca<strong>s</strong>a <code>/ˈkasa/</code></td>
<td>Voiceless sibilant. In much of Spain it is often apical/retracted <code>[s̺]</code>, made with the tongue tip slightly raised. Do not voice it as English <code>/z/</code> between vowels.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/x/</code></td>
<td><strong>j</strong>amón <code>/xaˈmon/</code>, <strong>g</strong>ente <code>/ˈxente/</code></td>
<td>Voiceless velar fricative. Back of tongue approaches the soft palate; create friction. Stronger than English <code>/h/</code>.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/ʝ/</code></td>
<td><strong>y</strong>o <code>/ʝo/</code>, <strong>ll</strong>ave <code>/ˈʝaβe/</code></td>
<td>Voiced palatal approximant/fricative. In most of Spain, <strong>y</strong> and <strong>ll</strong> are pronounced the same. After pause, nasal, or <code>/l/</code>, it may sound stronger, like <code>[ɟʝ]</code>.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h3>Affricate</h3>

<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>IPA</th>
<th>Example</th>
<th>Articulation</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><code>/tʃ/</code></td>
<td><strong>ch</strong>ico <code>/ˈtʃiko/</code></td>
<td>Voiceless postalveolar affricate, like English <em>ch</em> in <em>church</em>, but usually shorter and cleaner.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h3>Nasals</h3>

<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>IPA</th>
<th>Example</th>
<th>Articulation</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><code>/m/</code></td>
<td><strong>m</strong>ano <code>/ˈmano/</code></td>
<td>Bilabial nasal. Lips closed; air through nose.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/n/</code></td>
<td><strong>n</strong>ada <code>/ˈnaða/</code></td>
<td>Alveolar/dental nasal. Tongue touches near the teeth or alveolar ridge; air through nose.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/ɲ/</code></td>
<td>ni<strong>ñ</strong>o <code>/ˈniɲo/</code>, a<strong>ñ</strong>o <code>/ˈaɲo/</code></td>
<td>Palatal nasal. Middle of tongue touches the hard palate. Similar to <em>ny</em>, but it is one sound, not two separate sounds.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<div class="note">
<p>
Spanish <code>/n/</code> changes place depending on the next consonant:
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>un beso</strong> → <code>[um ˈbeso]</code></li>
  <li><strong>un gato</strong> → <code>[uŋ ˈɡato]</code></li>
  <li><strong>un chico</strong> → often <code>[un ˈtʃiko]</code> or slightly adjusted to the following sound</li>
</ul>
</div>

<h3>Liquids: L, Tap R, and Trilled R</h3>

<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>IPA</th>
<th>Example</th>
<th>Articulation</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><code>/l/</code></td>
<td><strong>l</strong>una <code>/ˈluna/</code></td>
<td>Alveolar lateral. Tongue tip touches near the alveolar ridge or teeth; air flows around the sides. Spanish <code>/l/</code> is generally clearer than English dark L.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/ɾ/</code></td>
<td>pe<strong>r</strong>o <code>/ˈpeɾo/</code></td>
<td>Single tap R. Tongue quickly taps the alveolar ridge once. Very short and light.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/r/</code></td>
<td>pe<strong>rr</strong>o <code>/ˈpero/</code>, <strong>r</strong>ojo <code>/ˈroxo/</code></td>
<td>Trilled R. Tongue tip vibrates rapidly against the alveolar ridge. Used for written <strong>rr</strong> and word-initial <strong>r</strong>.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/ʎ/</code></td>
<td>traditional <strong>ll</strong>ave <code>/ˈʎaβe/</code></td>
<td>Palatal lateral. Traditional distinction between <strong>ll</strong> and <strong>y</strong>. Most modern Spanish speakers use <code>/ʝ/</code> for both, so this is optional.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h2>4. Key Spanish Allophones</h2>

<h3>1. B/V: <code>[b]</code> vs <code>[β̞]</code></h3>

<p>
Spanish <strong>b</strong> and <strong>v</strong> are the same phoneme: <code>/b/</code>.
</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Position</th>
<th>Pronunciation</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>After pause or nasal</td>
<td>Strong <code>[b]</code></td>
<td><strong>vino</strong> <code>[ˈbino]</code>, <strong>un vaso</strong> <code>[um ˈbaso]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Between vowels or after most sounds</td>
<td>Soft <code>[β̞]</code></td>
<td><strong>la vida</strong> <code>[la ˈβ̞iða]</code>, <strong>el vaso</strong> <code>[el ˈβ̞aso]</code></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>
For <code>[β̞]</code>, bring the lips close together but do not fully close them. It is softer than English <code>/v/</code>; do not use your teeth.
</p>

<h3>2. D: <code>[d̪]</code> vs <code>[ð̞]</code></h3>

<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Position</th>
<th>Pronunciation</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>After pause, nasal, or <code>/l/</code></td>
<td>Strong dental <code>[d̪]</code></td>
<td><strong>día</strong> <code>[ˈd̪ia]</code>, <strong>un día</strong> <code>[un ˈd̪ia]</code>, <strong>el día</strong> <code>[el ˈd̪ia]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Between vowels or after most sounds</td>
<td>Soft <code>[ð̞]</code></td>
<td><strong>cada</strong> <code>[ˈkað̞a]</code>, <strong>la duda</strong> <code>[la ˈð̞uð̞a]</code></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>
This soft <code>[ð̞]</code> is similar to English <em>th</em> in <em>this</em>, but usually weaker and less fricative.
</p>

<h3>3. G: <code>[ɡ]</code> vs <code>[ɣ̞]</code></h3>

<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Position</th>
<th>Pronunciation</th>
<th>Example</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>After pause or nasal</td>
<td>Strong <code>[ɡ]</code></td>
<td><strong>gato</strong> <code>[ˈɡato]</code>, <strong>un gato</strong> <code>[uŋ ˈɡato]</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Between vowels or after most sounds</td>
<td>Soft <code>[ɣ̞]</code></td>
<td><strong>amigo</strong> <code>[aˈmiɣ̞o]</code>, <strong>la guerra</strong> <code>[la ˈɣ̞era]</code></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h3>4. Spanish R Rules</h3>

<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Spelling</th>
<th>Pronunciation</th>
<th>Examples</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Single <strong>r</strong> between vowels</td>
<td>Tap <code>/ɾ/</code></td>
<td><strong>pero</strong> <code>/ˈpeɾo/</code>, <strong>caro</strong> <code>/ˈkaɾo/</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>rr</strong></td>
<td>Trill <code>/r/</code></td>
<td><strong>perro</strong> <code>/ˈpero/</code>, <strong>carro</strong> <code>/ˈkaro/</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Word-initial <strong>r</strong></td>
<td>Trill <code>/r/</code></td>
<td><strong>rojo</strong> <code>/ˈroxo/</code>, <strong>rápido</strong> <code>/ˈrapido/</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>After <strong>n</strong>, <strong>l</strong>, or <strong>s</strong></td>
<td>Usually trill <code>/r/</code></td>
<td><strong>Enrique</strong> <code>/enˈrike/</code>, <strong>alrededor</strong> <code>/alreðeˈðoɾ/</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Final <strong>r</strong></td>
<td>Usually tap <code>/ɾ/</code>, sometimes stronger in emphasis</td>
<td><strong>comer</strong> <code>/koˈmeɾ/</code>, <strong>hablar</strong> <code>/aˈβ̞laɾ/</code></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

