</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>j</strong></td>
<td><code>/x/</code></td>
<td><strong>jamón</strong> <code>/xaˈmon/</code>, <strong>ojo</strong> <code>/ˈoxo/</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>ll</strong>, <strong>y</strong></td>
<td>Usually <code>/ʝ/</code></td>
<td><strong>llave</strong> <code>/ˈʝaβe/</code>, <strong>yo</strong> <code>/ʝo/</code></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<h2>6. Málaga and Andalusian Spanish: What You Will Hear Locally</h2>

<p>
In Málaga, many speakers use Andalusian features. These are normal and native, but if your target is standard “classic” Castilian Spanish, practice the standard forms on the right.
</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Feature</th>
<th>Málaga / Andalusian Tendency</th>
<th>Standard Castilian Target</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Final <code>/s/</code></td>
<td>Often aspirated or dropped: <strong>los amigos</strong> → <code>[loh aˈmiɣoh]</code> or <code>[lo aˈmiɣo]</code></td>
<td>Pronounce final <code>/s/</code>: <code>/los aˈmiɣos/</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/s/</code> vs <code>/θ/</code></td>
<td>Some areas have <em>seseo</em> or <em>ceceo</em>, merging the sounds.</td>
<td>Keep them distinct: <strong>casa</strong> <code>/ˈkasa/</code> vs <strong>caza</strong> <code>/ˈkaθa/</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>/x/</code></td>
<td>Often softer, like <code>[h]</code>: <strong>jamón</strong> <code>[haˈmon]</code></td>
<td>Use velar <code>[x]</code>: <code>/xaˈmon/</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Final <code>/d/</code></td>
<td>May weaken or disappear: <strong>Madrid</strong> → <code>[maˈðɾi]</code></td>
<td>Keep a light final consonant: <code>/maˈðɾið/</code> or careful <code>/maˈdɾid/</code></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>-ado</strong></td>
<td>Often <code>[ao]</code>: <strong>cansado</strong> → <code>[kanˈsao]</code></td>
<td>Standard: <code>/kanˈsaðo/</code></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<div class="note">
<p>
For daily life in Málaga, understanding these local features is very useful. But for a standard Castilian target, keep:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>final <code>/s/</code> clear,</li>
  <li><code>/s/</code> and <code>/θ/</code> separate,</li>
  <li><code>/x/</code> stronger than English <code>/h/</code>,</li>
  <li>unstressed vowels clear, not reduced.</li>
</ul>
</div>

