<h2>11. Daily Practice Routine</h2>

<p>Use this 25–30 minute routine.</p>

<h3>1. Vowel Warm-up: 3 minutes</h3>

<p>Say slowly:</p>

<p><code>/a e i o u/</code></p>

<p>Then say:</p>

<p><strong>pa pe pi po pu</strong><br>
<strong>ta te ti to tu</strong><br>
<strong>ka ke ki ko ku</strong></p>

<h3>2. One Sound Focus: 7 minutes</h3>

<p>Choose one difficult sound, for example <code>/r/</code>, <code>/ɾ/</code>, <code>/θ/</code>, or <code>/x/</code>.</p>

<ol>
<li>Say the sound alone.</li>
<li>Say it in syllables.</li>
<li>Say it in words.</li>
<li>Say it in sentences.</li>
<li>Record yourself and compare with native audio.</li>
</ol>

<h3>3. Minimal Pairs: 7 minutes</h3>

<p>Choose one pair set:</p>

<ul>
<li><code>/ɾ/</code> vs <code>/r/</code>: pero/perro, caro/carro</li>
<li><code>/s/</code> vs <code>/θ/</code>: casa/caza, tasa/taza</li>
<li><code>/e/</code> vs <code>/i/</code>: peso/piso, mesa/misa</li>
<li><code>/o/</code> vs <code>/u/</code>: coro/curo, solo/suelo-like practice</li>
</ul>

<h3>4. Shadowing: 10 minutes</h3>

<p>
Use native audio from Spain. For standard Castilian, choose speakers from Madrid, Castilla y León, Aragón, La Rioja, or similar regions.
</p>

<ol>
<li>Listen once without speaking.</li>
<li>Mark the stressed syllables.</li>
<li>Repeat phrase by phrase.</li>
<li>Speak at the same time as the audio.</li>
<li>Record yourself and compare rhythm, vowels, and consonants.</li>
</ol>

<h3>5. Free Speech: 3 minutes</h3>

<p>
Talk about your day in Spanish while focusing on one target. Example target: pronounce every final <code>/s/</code> clearly.
</p>

