<h3>Reading Passage</h3>

<p>
<strong>
Me llamo Carlos y vivo en Málaga. Me gusta caminar por la ciudad, tomar café con mis amigos y practicar español todos los días.
Quiero hablar con una pronunciación clara, natural y correcta.
</strong>
</p>

<p>Standard careful IPA:</p>

<p>
<code>/me ˈʝamo ˈkaɾlos i ˈbiβo en ˈmalaɣa. me ˈɡusta kamiˈnaɾ poɾ la θjuˈðað, toˈmaɾ kaˈfe kon mis aˈmiɣos i pɾaktiˈkaɾ espaˈɲol ˈtoðos los ˈdias. ˈkjeɾo aˈβlaɾ kon una pɾonunθjaˈθjon ˈklaɾa, natuˈɾal i koˈrekta/</code>
</p>

<h2>13. Best Practice Strategy</h2>

<ol>
<li><strong>Pick a target accent.</strong> For this guide: standard European/Castilian Spanish.</li>
<li><strong>Keep vowels pure.</strong> This is one of the fastest ways to sound more Spanish.</li>
<li><strong>Master dental <code>/t d/</code>.</strong> This immediately reduces an English accent.</li>
<li><strong>Do not pronounce Spanish V like English V.</strong> Use <code>/b/</code> and soft <code>[β̞]</code>.</li>
<li><strong>Practice <code>/ɾ/</code> and <code>/r/</code> separately.</strong> They can change meaning.</li>
<li><strong>For Castilian Spanish, keep <code>/s/</code> and <code>/θ/</code> distinct.</strong></li>
<li><strong>In Málaga, learn local pronunciation passively, but choose deliberately what you imitate.</strong></li>
</ol>

